4":"1354","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","England. United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Tilston, Cheshire, England":"Tilston, Cheshire, England","London, Middelsex, England":"City of London, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Middlesex, England":"Middlesex, England","London, England":"London, England"},"en":{"1430–1485":"1430–1485","1383–1440":"1383–1440","1435–Female":"1435–Deceased","1458–1485":"1458–1485","1457–Male":"1457–Deceased","1350–1421":"1350–1421","1354–1422":"1354–1422","1440":"1440","1350":"1350","1383":"1383","1459":"1459","1458":"1458","1457":"1457","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1422":"1422","1421":"1421","about 1457":"about 1457","1354":"1354","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","England. United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Tilston, Cheshire, England":"Tilston, Cheshire, England","London, Middelsex, England":"City of London, England, United Kingdom","Middlesex, England":"Middlesex, England","London, England":"London, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bird","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: nickname for a young or a small and slender person, from Middle English <i>brid</i>, <i>bird</i>, <i>burd</i> (Old English <i>bird</i>, <i>brid</i>, perhaps also <i>byrd</i>) ‘bird, young bird’, also ‘young man, young woman, child’.","Irish: Anglicized form of a number of Irish names erroneously thought to contain the element <i>éan</i> ‘bird’, in particular <i>Ó hÉinigh</i> (see   Heagney  ), <i>Ó hÉanna</i> (see   Heaney  ), <i>Ó hÉanacháin</i> (see   Heneghan  ), and <i>Mac an Déaghanaigh</i> (see   McEneaney  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘bird’, as for example German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Vogel  , French   Loiseau  , Czech <b>Ptáček</b> (see   Ptacek  ) and <b>Pták</b>, Polish   Ptak  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kingbird","meanings":["Native American (Chippewa; also <b>King Bird</b>): translation into English of the Chippewa personal name <i>Ogimaa-bines(i)</i>, meaning literally ‘the bird that is king’ and referring to the mythological bird-like creature thunderbird. See also   Bird   4.","History: The progenitor of the large family of the Kingbirds from the Red Lake, MN, was Ogimaa-bines, a musical gifted Chippewa spiritual leader."]},{"name":"Byrd","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Bird  ."]},{"name":"Heaney","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Aidan, Malachy, Nuala, Ronan.","Irish:","Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hÉanna</b> and <b>Ó hÉinne</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Éanna</i>’, a very common personal name of uncertain meaning. It was borne by various early Christian saints, most notably Saint Éanna of Aran. The name has been erroneously understood as containing the element <i>éan</i> ‘bird’ and as a result the surname was sometimes Anglicized as   Bird  ."]},{"name":"Blackbird","meanings":["Native American (also <b>Black Bird</b>): translation into English of a personal name such as Lakota Sioux <i>Ziŋtkala Sapa</i>, which is composed of <i>ziŋtkala</i> ‘bird’ and <i>sapa</i> ‘black’. See also   Bird   4.","English (Durham): nickname for someone with a dark beard, from Middle English <i>blak</i> ‘black’ + <i>berd</i> ‘beard’ (Old English <i>blæc</i> + <i>beard</i>)."]},{"name":"Burd","meanings":["English: variant of   Bird  .","Jewish (from Poland and Ukraine): nickname for a man with a notable beard, from a southern Yiddish pronunciation of Yiddish <i>bord</i> ‘beard’."]},{"name":"Burt","meanings":["English (southern): variant of   Bird  ,   Bright  , or   Burd  .","German: Middle High German <i>burt</i> ‘that which is due or proper’, therefore a nickname for someone who has fulfilled his obligations properly.","Jewish (from Poland and Ukraine): variant of   Burd  ."]},{"name":"Hummingbird","meanings":["Native American (Cherokee): translation into English of a personal name based on the Cherokee name <i>walela</i> for a hummingbird. See also   Bird   4."]},{"name":"Heagney","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hÉignigh</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Éigneach</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘forceful’. The spelling of the Irish name was often simplified to <b>Ó hÉinigh</b> and then Anglicized as   Heaney   or ‘translated’ as   Bird  , the latter because of a perceived similarity to <i>éan</i> ‘bird’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":25,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When John Bird was born in 1430, in Middlesex, England, his father, John Bird, was 80 and his mother, Alice Bulkeley, was 77. He married Agnes Bickworth in 1459, in City of London, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1485, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1430–1485":"1430–1485","1383–1440":"1383–1440","1435–Female":"1435–Surnud","1458–1485":"1458–1485","1457–Male":"1457–Surnud","1350–1421":"1350–1421","1354–1422":"1354–1422","1440":"1440","1350":"1350","1383":"1383","1459":"1459","1458":"1458","1457":"1457","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1422":"1422","1421":"1421","about 1457":"umbes 1457","1354":"1354","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","England. United Kingdom":"Inglismaa,